Crime魁 Putin (Note: "罪魁" literally means "culprit" or "chief criminal," but the phrase "罪魁普京" is likely a mistranslation or misphrasing. The intended meaning might be "Putin is the chief culprit" or "Putin is the main criminal.")
Moscow — Medical experts from Germany, France, and Sweden unanimously stated that Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is the biggest opponent of Russian President Vladimir Putin and the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Fortunately, due to Navalny's survival, the relationship between Russia and Germany did not deteriorate.
In order to demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel announced that Navalny is a "victim persecuted for exercising freedom of speech."
In her view, this incident is extremely serious, and only the Russian government can and must respond to it.
She emphasized that the entire world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the investigation proves that the Russian government is the main culprit behind the incident, the European Commission will impose a new round of sanctions.
Nevertheless, according to the regulations of the Chemical Weapons Convention, poisoning is a prohibited act.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok against its political opponents.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both of them survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov insisted that "there is no evidence to accuse the Russian government."
Sergei Naryshkin, the Director of the Russian Foreign Intelligence Service, even claimed that this was the act of Western intelligence agencies, attempting to tarnish the credibility of the Russian government.
Naretsky's argument is clearly fallacious, but he also points out a fact: the Navalny incident has been more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
It is utterly indefensible to poison a prominent political opponent with a toxin developed by the former Soviet Union shortly before an upcoming election.
This timing is even more intriguing, especially as the people of the neighboring country Belarus are protesting the August elections.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny incident was particularly confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before carrying out the crime?
If, as Germany claims, the Russian government was indeed behind this murder, then it was also a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of the international political arena (the main antagonist in the movie Star Wars), intervening in the U.S. elections, inciting street protests in France, luring Britain into Brexit, and supporting Syria's Bashar al-Assad.
As a former KGB agent, he is shrewd, far-sighted, and cunning.
Then why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why could Navalny flee to Germany? Moreover, he was soon diagnosed as having been poisoned.
Now, Putin is facing international condemnation and sanctions, and the second phase of the Nord Stream gas pipeline to Germany is at risk of cancellation.
This murder was clearly not worth it.
In fact, this has further fueled public opposition against the wrongdoing of the Russian authorities.
Even if it was indeed not Putin who did it, accusing Western intelligence agencies would be even more excessive.
If such allegations were true, scientists from Germany and Sweden would not have disclosed the fact that Novichok is a nerve agent.
More possibilities stem from conspiracies plotted by Putin's inner political circle.
Perhaps Putin needs Navalny to keep quiet before the election, or perhaps it's because of his anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers, although loyal, are quite foolish; they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, and only a few involved knew the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts have had similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza was the coordinator of the Khodorkovsky Inquiry Commission.
The poisoning of Peter Verzilov, publisher of the independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on abuses of power within the Russian judiciary.
This can be traced even further back to 2006, when Alexander Litvinenko, a former KGB officer, was poisoned. Alexander Litvinenko often criticized Russia's security agencies.
Just as in the case of Navalny, such poisoning attempts often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a liberal journalist from the newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a plane flying from Moscow to Beslan. Although she survived the poisoning, she was shot dead in an elevator in her apartment building two years later.
As Putin said, her death caused significant damage to the image of the Russian government.
This is not an excuse for the Kremlin.
Whether or not Putin personally directed it, the system he created allowed such crimes to occur. This system is both ineffective and useless, a farce involving shameless actors.
Navalny's death is the desired outcome of the Kremlin, and satisfying their master Putin is the ultimate goal of the lackeys.
Within Putin's inner circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if their poisoning attempt failed, they would not be punished.
Because they did it for the president's benefit.
Those who want to find evidence of poisoning might be disappointed.
All that said, the Kremlin is the culprit.
Western countries must clearly state their positions and impose sanctions on Russia even if their own economies are affected.
Putin created a system centered around himself.
All the responsibility in Russia is his own.
